annotation.TEXT: Good thing I had Yoshi there!
Demo count: 4
Whoops! I hit the wrong button by accident. Okay, so it looks like pressing Select on the overworld brings you back to this world select screen.
However, before I end the video, there's something I want to show off...

Whoa, what the? I came out of the same pipe I went in! Also, the game let me reenter when I reflexively hit down when I saw those super koopas. But, let me guess... Yeah, the blocks are all duds this time.
Alright, now can I perhaps use the bonus room to farm capes?
It's good to know that these line-guided lifts work fine. I mean, SMB3 handled them with no problem.
Oh, man. This part's going to be tricky with this game's jumping physics and lack of cape gliding...
Oh, you know what? I think these blocks are actually sprites. Seems weird, but maybe it's the only way this bonus room would work at all on the NES as far as I know...
Whoa! I thought that should've hit me! Well, it seems cape spinning is pretty effective, and it can one-shot a Chuck and block baseballs, just like it should.
And now to begin the Donut Plains. I wonder how (or if) this game handles capes...
Lava Lotus seems to perform (and get killed) like normal.
Still, this game couldn't have had me come out of a different pipe, like the one just to the right? Even SMB and SMB3 had no problem with that, but maybe this game's imitating Super Mario Land.
FINISH!!!
Demo count: 3
Still, what could it represent? The underground level Donut Plains 2? Well, knowing this game, maybe.
Gah, those stupid super koopas! They're in the worst spot! Was that pipe exit even playtested? (Actually, I doubt much (if any) of the game was even playtested.)
Oh, what? How come I didn't kill that piranha on contact while invincible? Also, Chuck seems to be the same way. (But I remember killing goombas back in YI2 on contact during my star power there...)
Alright, let's try this again, and maybe not stupidly die to the first enemy like that...
Okay, now Mikex62Robloxian has told me that if you pause the game, and then press Up, Right, A, Down, Right, B, Up, Left...
That wasn't what I meant to show you though (but it's nice to know that you can return to the world select screen).
Alright, let's try this again... And maybe not fall blindly into a pit like that.
Oh, a bonus room! Huzzah! I'm glad I was still checking every pipe!
I'm glad that level's over with, though it might be good to come back to for capes later.
Oh, do we have working ON/OFF switches here? (It says "OFF" to begin with, in case you can't see it.)
Now I just gotta aim my jump right...
So, it looks like the next level is a ghost house, and after that will be the second castle, but those will have to wait until next time!
Now, what's this? Is that another Yoshi's House? Well, maybe that house icon represents a different level entirely...
I don't know why I'm going for the final Yoshi coin here. Also, those two regular coins are too low to collect from the platform.
You wanna let me saddle up there, buddy? Thank you!
Yeah, the block changed to "ON", and while there was no visible change in the lines, the platform did change course. I don't think SMB3 had anything like that.
Yay, regular coins! I'd better get them, because Yoshi coins are worthless, and you can't get coins from blocks.
Well, this seems to work like you'd expect, except the coins you get, while being worth 100 points, don't actually add to your coin counter!
Hello, and welcome back to Super Mario World NES! Last time, I defeated Reznor in Iggy's Castle for some reason.
I can also take stupid hits as well... Oh, hi, Yoshi!
WAAAHHH!!! Yeah, this code causes a screen with this crazy sun to appear! (And according to IgorHorst, this is the JY Company's Sun, who published some Hummer Team games, including SMW NES.)
Okay, let's try this again... But at least I get to start from midpoint this time.
...Okay... Let's try this yet again! (Wow, I'm sucking here!)
Oh, come on! Why did there have to be a pit right there?
Okay, one more coin and I'll get a 1-up! (Assuming THAT works properly, that is!)

...And at this point, no button inputs seem to do anything, so I'll have to load the savestate that I made before inputting this code to resume the game. So, until next time, folks. To be continued...
Error: Cannot find REALITY.SYS. Universe halted.

Now, that's interesting how Chuck's baseballs actually stop (with a sound and graphical effect!) when they hit a wall or block here. That's different from the original game, where they pass through everything.
Okay, I'm pretty sure there's a cape to be gotten here by normal stomping a super koopa. So, Yoshi, wait here for a moment, please.
Interestingly, if you look closely at blocks, you might see that some have darker outlines. They've got stuff in them!
Okay, I'm not gonna let that same guy kill me this time!
Hmm... Maybe I should actually try to get some lives here...
Ow, but maybe I can get a feather here...
After what DP1 put me through, I'm surprised I didn't die at all in this level!
Well, the cape doesn't open, but otherwise it seems that flying controls sort of like in the original.
The cape did indeed reappear, but if I have to take a forced hit coming out of that pipe while super, there's no point.
Got him! Alright, Yoshi, let's go!
Yay, I can cape spin fireballs too, just like I should be able to.

Nope, it's actually just another Yoshi's House! Now, why would that be necessary? I mean, yeah, I do get another life upon exiting it, but you can revisit levels in this game, so there's nothing stopping you from going back to the first Yoshi's House...
Also, you can't glide down slowly, unlike in the original (and unlike SMB3's raccoon/tanooki forms). I'm going to have to remember not to try gliding during tricky jumps.
The vine block's position was obvious, despite it being in a different spot from the original. Also, all action does indeed freeze while the vine is growing for whatever reason.
Whoa, that was weird! What was I walking on there? Also, are there no bonus rooms at all in this game?
Yay, another cape! (I guess that block represents the green ! block that's there in the original.)
I don't know why that previous block didn't work when I hit it, but it was probably a feather that I didn't need.
So, B does a cape spin, but if you cape spin in midair, it feels like it just turns your jump into a spin jump.
Okay, three out of five isn't bad.
Nope, it's Donut Plains 3! Okay, that makes perfect sense to me!
Well, that was kind of a dumb hit, but at least I had a reserve cape.
Okay, no accidents there this time. Now, let's stay on the ground level.
Interestingly, the second block started at "OFF", even though I changed the first one to "ON". Also, yay, getting 100 coins does give a 1-up (which is also worth 1000 points, interestingly enough)!
Yay for a possibly unnecessary (or possibly necessary, knowing this game) screen transition.
Okay, so red koopas can walk off ledges in this game. Actually, I think that guy was the parakoopa I stomped a few seconds ago, so maybe it's imitating SMB1 in that regard.
To err is human, but really fouling things up requires a computer!
Wait, what? Okay, unless I counted wrong, I think that guy took four stomps to defeat. That's weird...
ARGH!!! I had a feeling that would happen, so I was trying to avoid the fuzzies. Yeah, Yoshi's not immune to them here, and he can't even stomp them.
Nuts! Don't panic! I'm still alive, and I can do this!
Huh. You can't grab the vine by pressing down. Only by pressing up. I'd better remember that.
Also, the hit blocks are becoming brown used blocks and O blocks here with no problem, so why couldn't hit blocks become brown used blocks elsewhere?
And it put me on the world 2 castle, but I'm going to backtrack to a completed level for this (even though I could probably do this in any level).
And there's the goal. You know what? Screw you, Chuck!
Demo count: 2
Okay, looks like the rotating platform works. (It better! I'd be in trouble if it didn't!)
Hey, you! Come back here and give me another cape! (Why does your horizontal movement slow down when you jump in this game anyway? That's kind of dumb.)
CONGRESS.SYS corrupted: Reboot Washington DC? (Y/N)
Oh, come on! That mushroom went to the right the last two times! What, is its direction randomly determined?
Aw, can't go out the way I came in. Well, whatever.
Well, alright. The super koopa here did indeed give me a cape (and it also perished in one hit, so I guess there's no cape farming). Let's see how it performs...
Okay, bonus room time! ...Or not... Come on, game. You proved back in DP1 that you can do bonus rooms, and this would be where that type of bonus room belongs!
Thanks, star power, for running out at the last second on me there. (At least in most Mario games, you remain invincible for a little bit longer after the star music ends...)
Demo count: 5
Okay, well, is this the actual Donut Plains 2?
